```javascript
let arr = [5, 1, 3, 8, 9];
arr.sort((a, b) => {
  return a - b;
});
console.log(arr);
```

This will output:

```
[1, 3, 5, 8, 9]
```

In this code, the `sort()` method is used with a compare function that compares two elements of the array and returns a negative, positive or zero value depending on whether the first element is less than, greater than, or equal to the second element. The `sort()` method uses these values to sort the array in descending order.

